\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
The shell method is a powerful technique for calculating volumes of solids of revolution. This method is particularly useful when the solid is generated by revolving a region around an axis that is parallel to the axis of integration. In this chapter, we will explore the application of the shell method to various functions and regions, focusing on the mathematical setup and execution of the necessary integrals.

Understanding the shell method requires a solid foundation in calculus, particularly in integration techniques. Students will benefit from reviewing the fundamental concepts of integration, as well as the geometric interpretation of volumes of revolution. The shell method offers an alternative to the washer method, allowing for more flexibility in certain scenarios, especially when dealing with vertical or horizontal rotations.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Theory of Shell Method}\label{sec:theory}\nopagebreak[4]
The shell method involves calculating the volume of a solid of revolution by integrating cylindrical shells. When a region is revolved around an axis, each infinitesimal shell contributes to the total volume. The formula for the volume \( V \) of a solid generated by revolving a region between the curves \( y = f(x) \) and \( y = g(x) \) from \( x = a \) to \( x = b \) around the y-axis is given by:

\[
V = 2\pi \int_{a}^{b} (radius)(height) \, dx
\]

In this context, the radius is the distance from the axis of rotation to the shell, and the height is the difference between the upper and lower functions over the interval of integration. For example, if revolving around the y-axis, the radius is simply \( x \), while the height is determined by the function values at that radius.

To illustrate this method, consider the region bounded by the curve \( y = f(x) \) and the lines \( x = a \) and \( x = b \). When this region is revolved around the y-axis, the resulting solid consists of concentric cylindrical shells, each with a thickness of \( dx \). The volume of each shell can be expressed as the product of the circumference of the shell, the height of the shell, and the thickness.

