\section*{Key Terms}
\subsection*{Definite Integral}
A definite integral represents the accumulation of quantities over an interval, such as areas under curves. It is calculated using the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, which connects differentiation and integration. The notation $\int_a^b f(x) \, dx$ denotes the integration of function $f(x)$ from $a$ to $b$.

\subsection*{Signed Area}
Signed area considers the direction of areas relative to the x-axis, assigning negative values to areas below the axis. This concept is essential for calculating net area, reflecting the total accumulation of positive and negative values. It is crucial in applications like computing displacement in physics.

\subsection*{Antiderivative}
An antiderivative of a function is another function whose derivative is the original function. It is used to compute definite integrals by applying the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus. If $F'(x) = f(x)$, then $F(x)$ is an antiderivative of $f(x)$.

\subsection*{Fundamental Theorem of Calculus}
This theorem establishes the relationship between differentiation and integration, providing a method to evaluate definite integrals. It states that if $F(x)$ is an antiderivative of $f(x)$, then $\int_a^b f(x) \, dx = F(b) - F(a)$. This connection simplifies the computation of integrals.

\subsection*{Net Area}
Net area represents the total accumulation of areas above and below the x-axis, combining them to reflect the overall effect. It considers both positive and negative contributions, making it vital in describing physical phenomena like displacement and work done by a force.

\subsection*{Integration by Parts}
Integration by parts is a technique used to integrate products of functions by transforming them into simpler integrals. It is based on the product rule for differentiation and is expressed as $\int u \, dv = uv - \int v \, du$. This method is useful when direct integration is difficult.

\subsection*{Improper Integral}
An improper integral involves an infinite limit of integration or an integrand that becomes infinite within the interval. These integrals require careful evaluation using limits, often arising in problems with infinite domains or singularities.

\subsection*{Piecewise Function}
A piecewise function is defined by multiple sub-functions, each applying to specific intervals of the domain. These functions require special consideration in integration, as discontinuities and changes in definition must be managed by evaluating separate integrals for each segment.

\section*{Theory}
\subsection*{Introduction to Area Below x-axis and Signed Areas}
The concept of signed areas is fundamental in calculus, offering a nuanced understanding of how areas under a curve contribute to total accumulation. When integrating a function over an interval, the result can be positive or negative depending on whether the function lies above or below the x-axis. This distinction is crucial for computing the net area, which reflects the overall effect of both positive and negative contributions.

Understanding signed areas involves recognizing that the definite integral of a function over an interval $[a, b]$ accounts for regions beneath the x-axis by assigning them negative values. This approach is essential in fields like physics, where it aids in calculating displacements by considering the direction of motion. For instance, when a velocity function is integrated, the signed area represents the net displacement, accounting for both forward and backward motions.

Historically, the development of signed areas marked a significant advance in mathematical analysis, allowing scientists and engineers to model complex systems more accurately. The signed area provides a comprehensive picture of the accumulation of values over an interval, making it indispensable in various scientific and engineering applications. By understanding the role of signed areas, students can better appreciate how calculus models real-world phenomena, paving the way for advanced studies in multivariable integration and beyond.

\subsection*{Core Methods and Techniques}
The core methods for handling signed areas and areas below the x-axis are rooted in the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus. This theorem bridges differentiation and integration, allowing us to evaluate definite integrals by finding antiderivatives and computing differences at the bounds. An essential technique for simplifying complex integrals is integration by parts, which leverages the product rule for differentiation to transform integrals into more manageable forms.

When dealing with piecewise functions, special care must be taken to handle discontinuities. For instance, if a function changes direction within the integration interval, the integral must be split at the point of change, and separate calculations must be performed for each segment. This approach ensures accurate computation of signed areas, particularly when functions exhibit different behaviors across intervals.

These methods are indispensable for solving real-world problems involving variable forces and dynamic systems. By mastering these techniques, students can tackle complex calculus problems with confidence, applying their skills to diverse fields such as engineering, physics, and economics. Understanding the interplay between differentiation and integration lays the foundation for advanced calculus topics, including multivariable calculus and differential equations.

\subsection*{Advanced Applications and Improper Integrals}
Advanced applications of signed areas extend to scenarios involving improper integrals, where one or more limits of integration are infinite, or the integrand approaches infinity within the integration range. In such cases, limits are used to evaluate the integral as the interval approaches infinity, ensuring convergence is properly assessed. This concept is pivotal in fields like probability theory and quantum mechanics, where infinite domains are common.

Improper integrals also model real-world phenomena, such as charge distribution in electric fields or the behavior of particles in quantum systems. These applications require a deep understanding of limits and careful handling of singularities to ensure accurate results. Additionally, piecewise functions present challenges in integration, as discontinuities and varying definitions across intervals necessitate segment-wise evaluation and careful continuity management.

By mastering advanced techniques for handling improper integrals and piecewise functions, students can extend their calculus skills to a wider range of applications, including modeling complex systems and analyzing dynamic processes. This knowledge is essential for pursuing further studies in advanced calculus topics and applied mathematics, where calculus serves as a foundational tool for exploring the natural and physical sciences.

\subsection*{Summary, Synthesis, and Future Directions}
This section consolidates the key ideas from the lesson on signed areas and areas below the x-axis, emphasizing the importance of understanding the net area concept and its applications across various fields. By summarizing the most critical formulas and methods, students can better grasp how these concepts fit into the broader calculus framework.

Common pitfalls, such as errors in sign or misinterpretation of piecewise function behavior, are highlighted to help students avoid mistakes in their calculations. The section also previews the upcoming topic of multivariable integration, illustrating how the foundational skills acquired in this lesson will be applied to more complex systems involving multiple variables and dimensions.

Understanding the connections between signed areas, core methods, and advanced applications is crucial for students preparing to tackle more challenging calculus topics. By building a strong foundation in these concepts, students are well-equipped to explore the rich and diverse applications of calculus in the natural and physical sciences, engineering, and beyond.

