\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}\nopagebreak[4]

In calculus, integration by parts and trigonometric substitution are powerful techniques for solving integrals that are not straightforward. These methods extend the basic integration rules and are particularly useful for dealing with products of functions and integrals involving square roots. Integration by parts is derived from the product rule for differentiation and is used to transform an integral into a simpler form. Trigonometric substitution, on the other hand, leverages trigonometric identities to simplify integrals involving radicals. Understanding these techniques is crucial for tackling complex integration problems encountered in advanced mathematics courses.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Integration by Parts}\label{sec:integration_by_parts}\nopagebreak[4]

Integration by parts is a technique used to integrate products of functions. The method is based on the product rule for differentiation, which states that the derivative of a product of two functions is given by:

\[
\frac{d}{dx}(uv) = u \frac{dv}{dx} + v \frac{du}{dx}
\]

From this rule, the integration by parts formula can be derived:

\[
\int u \, dv = uv - \int v \, du
\]

This formula allows us to transform an integral of the form \(\int u \, dv\) into an integral that is potentially easier to evaluate. The key to using integration by parts effectively is choosing which part of the integrand to differentiate (\(u\)) and which part to integrate (\(dv\)). Generally, \(u\) is chosen to be a function that becomes simpler when differentiated, and \(dv\) is chosen to be a function that is easy to integrate.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}
\node (A) at (0,0) {\( u \)};
\node (B) at (2,0) {\( dv \)};
\node (C) at (0,-2) {\( du \)};
\node (D) at (2,-2) {\( v \)};
