Trigonometric substitution is an essential technique for solving integrals involving complex radicals. It simplifies the integration process by converting the problem into a trigonometric context, allowing for straightforward application of known identities.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Worked Examples}\label{sec:examples}\nopagebreak[4]

\begin{samepage}
\needspace{14\baselineskip}
\begin{examplebox}{Example 1: Basic Integration by Parts Example}
Use integration by parts to evaluate the integral \( \int x e^x \, dx \).
\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Integral: \( \int x e^x \, dx \)
\end{itemize}
\textbf{Required:} Evaluate the integral using integration by parts.
\end{examplebox}
\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Choose \( u \) and \( dv \)}\\
Let \( u = x \) and \( dv = e^x \, dx \).\\
\textbf{Step 2: Differentiate and Integrate}\\
Differentiate \( u \) to get \( du = dx \) and integrate \( dv \) to get \( v = e^x \).\\
\textbf{Step 3: Apply Integration by Parts Formula}\\
Substitute into \(\int u \, dv = uv - \int v \, du\): \[ x e^x - \int e^x \, dx = x e^x - e^x + C \]
\[\boxed{x e^x - e^x + C}\]
\end{solutionbox}
\begin{notebox}
Integration by parts is useful for integrals involving products of algebraic and exponential functions. Choosing the correct \( u \) and \( dv \) is crucial for simplifying the integral.
\end{notebox}
\end{samepage}

