\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}\nopagebreak[4]

Improper integrals are a fundamental concept in calculus, extending the idea of definite integrals to cases where the interval of integration is unbounded or the integrand has discontinuities. These integrals are crucial in various fields such as physics and engineering, where they model phenomena involving infinite or undefined behavior. Understanding improper integrals requires familiarity with limits, as they allow us to evaluate integrals that extend to infinity or approach singularities.

In this chapter, we will explore the theory behind improper integrals, focusing on their convergence and divergence. We will also examine techniques for evaluating these integrals using limits and comparison tests. The worked examples provided will illustrate the practical application of these concepts, reinforcing the theoretical knowledge and demonstrating their relevance in real-world scenarios.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Theory of Improper Integrals}\label{sec:theory}\nopagebreak[4]

Improper integrals arise in situations where the interval of integration is infinite or the integrand becomes unbounded within the interval. These integrals are classified into two types: those with infinite limits and those with integrands that approach infinity at some point within the interval. To evaluate improper integrals, we use limits to transform them into proper integrals. This process involves expressing the integral as a limit of a definite integral as the boundary approaches infinity or the point of discontinuity.

The convergence or divergence of an improper integral is determined by the behavior of the integrand as it approaches the boundary. For instance, the integral $\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^2} \, dx$ is improper due to its infinite upper limit. We evaluate it by considering the limit $\lim_{b \to \infty} \int_{1}^{b} \frac{1}{x^2} \, dx$. The antiderivative of $\frac{1}{x^2}$ is $-\frac{1}{x}$, and evaluating the definite integral gives $1 - \frac{1}{b}$. As $b$ approaches infinity, the term $\frac{1}{b}$ approaches zero, resulting in a finite limit of 1, indicating convergence.

Another method for evaluating improper integrals is the comparison test, where we compare the given integral with a known convergent or divergent integral. If the integrand is smaller than a known convergent integrand, the original integral converges; if larger than a divergent integrand, it diverges. This technique is particularly useful when dealing with complex functions that are difficult to integrate directly.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Worked Examples}\label{sec:examples}\nopagebreak[4]

\begin{samepage}
\needspace{14\baselineskip}
\begin{examplebox}{Example 1: Evaluating Convergence of an Improper Integral}
Determine if the integral $\int_{1}^{\infty} \frac{1}{x^2} \, dx$ converges.

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Integrand: $\frac{1}{x^2}$
\item Interval: $[1, \infty)$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Required:} Determine convergence of the integral.
\end{examplebox}

\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Express the integral as a limit}\\
Rewrite the integral to handle the infinite upper bound. This is necessary for proper evaluation. Formulate the integral as a limit.
\begin{align*}
\text{Formula: } \lim_{b \to \infty} \int_{1}^{b} \frac{1}{x^2} \, dx
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 2: Find the antiderivative}\\
Determine the antiderivative of the integrand. This step is essential for evaluating the definite integral. Use basic integration rules.
\begin{align*}
\text{Antiderivative: } -\frac{1}{x}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Evaluate the integral and take the limit}\\
Substitute the bounds into the antiderivative. Calculate the limit as $b$ approaches infinity. Conclude with the final result.
\begin{align*}
\text{Substitution: } -\frac{1}{b} + 1\\
\text{Limit: } \lim_{b \to \infty} (1 - \frac{1}{b}) = 1
\end{align*}

\[\boxed{1}\]
\end{solutionbox}

\begin{notebox}
Improper integrals require limits for evaluation. Convergence is determined by the behavior of the integrand. Understanding convergence is critical in applications.
\end{notebox}
\end{samepage}

