\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Risk Assessment and Management}\label{sec:risk}
\nopagebreak[4]

While expected value provides a useful summary measure, it does not capture the full picture of risk. Two alternatives may have identical expected values but very different risk profiles. \textbf{Risk assessment} involves measuring the variability or spread of possible outcomes around the expected value.

\begin{definitionbox}{Variance and Standard Deviation}
The variance of a random variable $X$ measures the expected squared deviation from the mean:
\begin{equation}
\text{Var}(X) = \sigma^2 = \sum_{i=1}^{n} P_i \cdot (x_i - E[X])^2
\end{equation}
The standard deviation $\sigma$ is the square root of the variance and has the same units as the original variable, making it more interpretable as a measure of spread.
\end{definitionbox}

A higher standard deviation indicates greater variability in outcomes and, consequently, higher risk. When comparing projects with similar expected values, risk-averse decision-makers typically prefer the alternative with lower standard deviation.

\subsection{Risk-Return Tradeoffs}

Engineering decisions often involve tradeoffs between expected return and risk. A project with higher expected value may also carry greater risk of loss. The \textbf{coefficient of variation} (CV) provides a normalized measure of risk relative to expected return:
\begin{equation}
CV = \frac{\sigma}{E[X]}
\end{equation}

This ratio enables comparison of risk across projects of different scales. A lower coefficient of variation indicates a more favorable risk-return profile.

\subsection{Decision Criteria Under Uncertainty}

Several decision criteria exist for selecting among alternatives under uncertainty:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
    \item \textbf{Expected Value Criterion}: Choose the alternative with the highest expected value.
    \item \textbf{Most Probable Outcome}: Choose based on the outcome with highest probability.
    \item \textbf{Maximin (Conservative)}: Choose the alternative with the best worst-case outcome.
    \item \textbf{Maximax (Optimistic)}: Choose the alternative with the best best-case outcome.
\end{itemize}

The expected value criterion is most commonly used in engineering economics because it accounts for all outcomes weighted by their likelihoods, providing a balanced assessment that neither ignores unlikely events nor overweights extreme scenarios.

