\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Identify Probabilities and Outcomes}\\
Probability of earning \$100,000 is 30\%. Probability of earning \$40,000 is 70\%. The outcomes are \$100,000 and \$40,000 respectively. Identifying probabilities and outcomes is crucial for calculating expected value.

\textbf{Step 2: Convert Probabilities to Decimal}\\
Convert percentages to decimal form for mathematical calculations:
\begin{align*}
30\% &= 0.30 \\
70\% &= 0.70
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Calculate Expected Value}\\
Apply the expected value formula by multiplying each outcome by its probability and summing:
\begin{align*}
\text{Expected Value} &= (P_1 \times V_1) + (P_2 \times V_2) \\
&= (0.30 \times \$100{,}000) + (0.70 \times \$40{,}000) \\
&= \$30{,}000 + \$28{,}000 \\
&= \$58{,}000
\end{align*}

\[\boxed{\text{Expected Value} = \$58{,}000}\]

\textit{Verification:} The sum of probabilities equals $0.30 + 0.70 = 1.00$, confirming a valid probability distribution. Recalculation confirms the expected value of \$58,000.
\end{solutionbox}

\begin{notebox}
Expected value provides a single measure of potential outcomes in uncertain conditions. Probabilities must be converted to decimals for calculations. The sum of probabilities in a decision scenario should equal 1. This technique is widely used in project feasibility studies to determine potential profitability.
\end{notebox}
