\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Calculate Expected Value for Project A}\\
Determine the expected profit for Project A using the expected value formula $EV = \sum(P_i \times V_i)$:
\begin{align*}
EV_A &= (0.70 \times \$100{,}000) + (0.30 \times (-\$30{,}000)) \\
&= \$70{,}000 - \$9{,}000 \\
&= \$61{,}000
\end{align*}
Project A's expected value of \$61,000 represents the average projected profit considering both gain and loss probabilities.

\textbf{Step 2: Calculate Expected Value for Project B}\\
Determine the expected profit for Project B:
\begin{align*}
EV_B &= (0.50 \times \$200{,}000) + (0.50 \times \$0) \\
&= \$100{,}000 + \$0 \\
&= \$100{,}000
\end{align*}
Project B's expected value of \$100,000 yields a higher average profit with no risk of loss.

\textbf{Step 3: Compare Expected Values}\\
Compare the expected values of both projects:
\begin{align*}
EV_B &= \$100{,}000 \\
EV_A &= \$61{,}000 \\
EV_B &> EV_A
\end{align*}
Since \$100,000 $>$ \$61,000, Project B has the higher expected value.

\[\boxed{\text{Choose Project B with EV} = \$100{,}000}\]

\textit{Verification:} Recalculation confirms both expected values. Project B is preferred due to its higher expected value and absence of potential loss.
\end{solutionbox}

\begin{notebox}
Expected value helps quantify potential outcomes in uncertain scenarios. Comparing expected values aids in selecting the most profitable project. Risk management is integral to engineering economics. Note that Project B also has zero downside risk, making it doubly attractive compared to Project A.
