\caption{Comparison of simple and compound interest growth over 10 years for a \$10,000 principal at 5\% annual interest rate. The linear growth of simple interest contrasts with the exponential growth of compound interest.}
\end{figure}

For short time horizons, the difference between simple and compound interest may be negligible. However, as time increases, the compound interest curve diverges increasingly from the simple interest line. This divergence is amplified by higher interest rates, making the choice between simple and compound interest particularly important for long-term financial planning.

The mathematical relationship between the two methods can be expressed as:
\begin{align*}
\text{Difference} &= P(1 + r)^t - P(1 + rt) \\
&= P\left[(1 + r)^t - (1 + rt)\right]
\end{align*}

This difference is always non-negative for $t \geq 1$ and $r > 0$, confirming that compound interest always yields at least as much as simple interest, with strict inequality for $t > 1$.

