\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Calculate Future Value Using Simple Interest}

Identify the formula for simple interest future value and substitute the given values:
\begin{align*}
FV &= P(1 + rt) \\
FV &= \$10,000(1 + 0.05 \times 5) \\
FV &= \$10,000(1 + 0.25) \\
FV &= \$10,000 \times 1.25 \\
FV &= \$12,500
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 2: Calculate Present Value Using Simple Interest}

Use the future value calculated in Step 1 and apply the simple interest present value formula to verify the initial principal:
\begin{align*}
PV &= \frac{FV}{1 + rt} \\
PV &= \frac{\$12,500}{1 + 0.05 \times 5} \\
PV &= \frac{\$12,500}{1.25} \\
PV &= \$10,000
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Calculate Future Value Using Compound Interest}

Identify the formula for compound interest future value and substitute the given values:
\begin{align*}
FV &= P(1 + r)^t \\
FV &= \$10,000(1 + 0.05)^5 \\
FV &= \$10,000(1.05)^5
\end{align*}

Calculate $(1.05)^5$:
\begin{align*}
(1.05)^5 &= 1.2762815625
\end{align*}

Therefore:
\begin{align*}
FV &= \$10,000 \times 1.2762815625 \\
FV &= \$12,762.82
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 4: Calculate Present Value Using Compound Interest}

Use the future value calculated in Step 3 and apply the compound interest present value formula:
\begin{align*}
PV &= \frac{FV}{(1 + r)^t} \\
PV &= \frac{\$12,762.82}{(1.05)^5} \\
PV &= \frac{\$12,762.82}{1.2762815625} \\
PV &= \$10,000
\end{align*}

\[\boxed{\text{Simple Interest: } FV = \$12,500 \quad | \quad \text{Compound Interest: } FV = \$12,762.82}\]
\end{solutionbox}

