\section{Summary}\label{sec:summary}
\nopagebreak[4]

This chapter introduced the fundamental concepts of simple and compound interest, along with the essential techniques for calculating future values and present values. The time value of money principle establishes that money available today is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its earning potential. Simple interest, calculated only on the original principal using $FV = P(1 + rt)$, produces linear growth over time. In contrast, compound interest, calculated on both principal and accumulated interest using $FV = P(1 + r)^t$, generates exponential growth that significantly exceeds simple interest over extended periods. Present value calculations, which discount future sums back to their current equivalent using $PV = FV/(1 + r)^t$, enable comparison of cash flows occurring at different times. These foundational concepts and formulas are essential tools for engineering economic analysis, supporting decisions about investments, project financing, and capital budgeting throughout an engineer's career.

