\end{figure}
\end{examplebox}

\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Identify Scenarios and Outcomes}\\
Consider the economic conditions that affect returns:
\begin{itemize}[noitemsep]
    \item Favorable economy: Higher returns realized
    \item Unfavorable economy: Lower returns or potential losses
    \item Assign probabilities $p_1$ and $p_2$ to each scenario where $p_1 + p_2 = 1$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Step 2: Calculate Expected Returns}\\
Compute the expected return for each option using probability-weighted averages:
\begin{align*}
E[R_A] &= (p_1 \times R_{A,\text{favorable}}) + (p_2 \times R_{A,\text{unfavorable}}) \\
E[R_B] &= (p_1 \times R_{B,\text{favorable}}) + (p_2 \times R_{B,\text{unfavorable}})
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Compare Expected Returns}\\
The option with the higher expected return is generally preferred:
\begin{align*}
\text{Compare: } E[R_A] \text{ vs. } E[R_B]
\end{align*}
\[\boxed{\text{Option B is preferred if it has a higher expected return.}}\]
\end{solutionbox}

\begin{notebox}
Understanding scenarios under uncertainty is crucial for decision making. Expected return is a valuable metric for comparing investment options, but risk tolerance must also be considered. Probabilistic models help evaluate both potential returns and associated risks.
\end{notebox}
\end{samepage}

