\section*{Key Terms}
\begin{samepage}
\needspace{8\baselineskip}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Time Value of Money:} The concept that money available at the present time is worth more than the same amount in the future due to its potential earning capacity. Notation: $PV = \frac{FV}{(1 + r)^n}$
    \item \textbf{Net Present Value:} A method used in capital budgeting to analyze the profitability of an investment or project by summing the present values of incoming and outgoing cash flows. Notation: $NPV = \sum_{t=0}^{n} \frac{C_t}{(1 + r)^t}$
    \item \textbf{Internal Rate of Return:} The discount rate that makes the net present value (NPV) of all cash flows from a particular project equal to zero. Notation: $0 = \sum_{t=0}^{n} \frac{C_t}{(1 + IRR)^t}$
    \item \textbf{Payback Period:} The time required for the return on an investment to repay the sum of the original investment. Notation: Payback Period = $\frac{Initial Investment}{Annual Cash Inflow}$
    \item \textbf{Marginal Cost:} The cost added by producing one additional unit of a product or service. Notation: $MC = \frac{\Delta TC}{\Delta Q}$
    \item \textbf{Marginal Revenue:} The additional revenue that will be generated by increasing product sales by one unit. Notation: $MR = \frac{\Delta TR}{\Delta Q}$
    \item \textbf{Economic Order Quantity:} The ideal order quantity a company should purchase to minimize its inventory costs such as holding costs, shortage costs, and order costs. Notation: $EOQ = \sqrt{\frac{2DS}{H}}$
    \item \textbf{Break-even Point:} The production level at which total revenues equals total expenses. Notation: $BEP = \frac{Fixed Costs}{Price - Variable Cost per Unit}$
\end{itemize}
\end{samepage}

