\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
\nopagebreak[4]
Engineering Economics is a vital field that connects economic theory with engineering practice. This discipline helps engineers and project managers evaluate the viability and potential profitability of projects. By understanding the principles of Engineering Economics, professionals can make informed decisions that optimize cost and maximize return on investment. This chapter introduces the fundamental concepts of Engineering Economics, explores its role in engineering practice, and provides an overview of the course structure.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Theory of Engineering Economics}\label{sec:theory}
\nopagebreak[4]
Engineering Economics, often considered a subset of industrial engineering, focuses on the use of economic principles to solve engineering problems. This involves techniques from statistical analysis, cost-benefit analysis, and methods of calculating depreciation. This section delves into the primary goals and methodologies of Engineering Economics, emphasizing its importance in strategic decision-making and project management.

\subsection{Basic Concepts}
The primary goal of Engineering Economics is to ensure that engineering decisions are made in a manner that considers both cost and efficiency. It seeks to identify the most cost-effective approach to achieve engineering goals, taking into account the financial and performance aspects of project management.

\subsection{Decision Making in Engineering Projects}
In Engineering Economics, decision-making is based on the comparison of the costs and benefits of potential project outcomes. This involves detailed financial analysis and forecasting to establish the economic viability of projects.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Worked Examples}\label{sec:examples}
\nopagebreak[4]
This section presents several worked examples that illustrate the application of Engineering Economics principles in real-world scenarios. Each example is carefully designed to reinforce the theoretical concepts discussed in the previous sections.

\needspace{14\baselineskip}
\begin{samepage}
