\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Identify Coordinates of Points}\\
We first identify the coordinates of both points that will be used in our calculation.
\begin{align*}
\text{Point } A: \quad (x_1, y_1) &= (2, 3) \\
\text{Point } B: \quad (x_2, y_2) &= (8, 11)
\end{align*}
Identifying the coordinates is crucial as they form the basis for calculating the slope.

\textbf{Step 2: Calculate the Difference in $Y$-Coordinates (Rise)}\\
We subtract the $y$-coordinate of Point $A$ from the $y$-coordinate of Point $B$ to find the rise.
\begin{align*}
\Delta y &= y_2 - y_1 \\
\Delta y &= 11 - 3 \\
\Delta y &= 8
\end{align*}
The rise is the change in vertical distance between the two points.

\textbf{Step 3: Calculate the Difference in $X$-Coordinates (Run)}\\
We subtract the $x$-coordinate of Point $A$ from the $x$-coordinate of Point $B$ to find the run.
\begin{align*}
\Delta x &= x_2 - x_1 \\
\Delta x &= 8 - 2 \\
\Delta x &= 6
\end{align*}
The run is the change in horizontal distance between the two points.

\textbf{Step 4: Calculate the Gradient Slope}\\
We divide the rise by the run to obtain the slope of the line.
\begin{align*}
m &= \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} \\
m &= \frac{8}{6} \\
m &= \frac{4}{3}
\end{align*}
The slope formula provides the steepness and direction of the line.

\textbf{Step 5: Interpret the Slope}\\
The slope of $\frac{4}{3}$ is positive, which means the line rises from left to right. For every 3 units of horizontal movement, the line rises 4 units vertically.
\begin{align*}
\text{Positive slope:} \quad m &= \frac{4}{3} \approx 1.33
\end{align*}

\[\boxed{m = \frac{4}{3}}\]
\end{solutionbox}

