\section{Summary}\label{sec:summary}
\nopagebreak[4]

The gradient slope of a line is a fundamental concept that quantifies the steepness and direction of a linear relationship between two variables. The slope is calculated using the formula $m = \frac{\Delta y}{\Delta x} = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$, where $\Delta y$ represents the vertical change (rise) and $\Delta x$ represents the horizontal change (run) between two points on the line. A positive slope indicates that the line rises from left to right, while a negative slope indicates that the line falls. The magnitude of the slope determines how steep the line is---larger absolute values correspond to steeper lines. This concept has widespread applications in engineering, including the design of ramps, roads, and roofs, as well as in analyzing rates of change in physical systems. Mastery of slope calculations provides an essential foundation for more advanced topics in mathematics and engineering.

