The power rules are particularly valuable in engineering applications where expressions involving multiple bases and nested exponents arise frequently. Circuit analysis, signal processing, and thermodynamic calculations all require fluent application of these rules to simplify complex formulas into manageable forms.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Worked Examples}\label{sec:examples}
\nopagebreak[4]

This section presents detailed solutions to representative problems involving the laws of exponents. Each example demonstrates the systematic application of the rules developed in previous sections, progressing from basic to advanced difficulty levels.

\begin{samepage}
\needspace{14\baselineskip}
\begin{examplebox}{Example 1: Understanding the Product of Powers Rule}
Simplify the expression: $(x^3) \cdot (x^4)$.

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
\item $x^3$
\item $x^4$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Required:} Simplified form of the expression.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[
    factor/.style={draw, circle, minimum size=0.8cm, inner sep=1pt},
    brace/.style={decorate, decoration={brace, amplitude=8pt}}
]
\node at (-4, 1.5) {$x^3 =$};
\foreach \i in {1,2,3} {
    \node[factor] (a\i) at (-3+\i*0.9, 1.5) {$x$};
}
\node at (-0.5, 1.5) {$\times$};
\node at (0.5, 1.5) {$\times$};

\node at (-4, 0) {$x^4 =$};
\foreach \i in {1,2,3,4} {
    \node[factor] (b\i) at (-3+\i*0.9, 0) {$x$};
}
\node at (-0.5, 0) {$\times$};
\node at (0.5, 0) {$\times$};
\node at (1.4, 0) {$\times$};

\draw[thick, -{Stealth}] (2.5, 0.75) -- (4, 0.75);
\node at (3.25, 1.2) {\small Add exponents};

\node at (5.5, 0.75) {$= x^{3+4} = x^7$};

\draw[brace] (-2.1, -0.6) -- (1.8, -0.6) node[midway, below=10pt] {7 total factors of $x$};
\end{tikzpicture}
