\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tabular}{@{}lll@{}}
\toprule
\textbf{Rule Name} & \textbf{Symbolic Representation} & \textbf{Example} \\
\midrule
Product of Powers & $x^a \cdot x^b = x^{a+b}$ & $2^3 \cdot 2^2 = 2^5$ \\
Quotient of Powers & $x^a / x^b = x^{a-b}$ & $3^5 / 3^2 = 3^3$ \\
Power of a Power & $(x^a)^b = x^{a \cdot b}$ & $(2^3)^2 = 2^6$ \\
\bottomrule
\end{tabular}
\captionof{table}{Table 1: Summary of Exponent Rules.}
\end{figure}

\end{examplebox}

\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Identify the Exponents}\\
The expression involves $x^3$ and $x^4$. We first identify that both terms share the same base, which is $x$. The exponents are 3 and 4, respectively.
\begin{align*}
\text{Base: } & x \\
\text{Exponents: } & 3 \text{ and } 4
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 2: Apply the Product of Powers Rule}\\
The product of powers rule states that when multiplying expressions with the same base, we add the exponents: $x^a \cdot x^b = x^{a+b}$. Applying this rule:
\begin{align*}
x^3 \cdot x^4 &= x^{3+4} \\
&= x^7
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Write the Simplified Expression}\\
Combining the result into a single exponential expression, we obtain the final simplified form.
\begin{align*}
x^3 \cdot x^4 &= x^7
\end{align*}

\[\boxed{x^7}\]

\textit{Verification:} We can verify by expanding both expressions: $x^3 = x \cdot x \cdot x$ (3 factors) and $x^4 = x \cdot x \cdot x \cdot x$ (4 factors). Multiplying these gives $3 + 4 = 7$ total factors of $x$, confirming $x^7$.
\end{solutionbox}

\begin{notebox}
\begin{itemize}
\item The product of powers rule simplifies multiplication of like bases by adding exponents.
\item Exponents are added, not multiplied, when using this rule.
\item This rule is foundational for handling higher-level algebraic expressions in engineering.
\end{itemize}
\end{notebox}
\end{samepage}

\begin{samepage}
\needspace{14\baselineskip}
\begin{examplebox}{Example 2: Understanding the Laws of Exponents in Engineering}
An engineering student is analyzing the power consumption of a device. Given the expression $(2^3) \times (2^4)$, which of the following represents the simplified form using the laws of exponents?

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
\item Expression: $(2^3) \times (2^4)$
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Required:} Simplified form of the expression.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
