\end{examplebox}

\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Identify the base and add the exponents}\\
We recognize that both terms in the expression share the same base, which is 2. According to the product of powers rule, when multiplying expressions with identical bases, we add the exponents.
\begin{align*}
\text{Formula: } & a^m \cdot a^n = a^{m+n} \\
\text{Substitution: } & 2^3 \cdot 2^4 = 2^{3+4} \\
\text{Result: } & 2^7
\end{align*}

The simplified form is $2^7$.

\[\boxed{2^7}\]

\textit{Verification:} We can verify by calculating separately: $2^3 = 8$ and $2^4 = 16$. Then $8 \times 16 = 128$. Checking: $2^7 = 128$. The answer is confirmed.
\end{solutionbox}

\begin{notebox}
\begin{itemize}
\item The product of powers rule helps simplify expressions with the same base.
\item Adding exponents when multiplying simplifies large calculations significantly.
\item Recognizing and applying the correct laws is essential for engineering problem-solving.
\item In power consumption analysis, such simplifications reduce computational complexity.
\end{itemize}
\end{notebox}
\end{samepage}

\begin{samepage}
\needspace{14\baselineskip}
\begin{examplebox}{Example 3: Advanced Application of the Laws of Exponents in Engineering}
Given the expression $\dfrac{(2^3 \cdot 5^2)^4}{10^2 \cdot 4^4}$, simplify using the laws of exponents.

\textbf{Given:}
\begin{itemize}
\item $2^3$, $5^2$
\item $(2^3 \cdot 5^2)^4$ in the numerator
\item $10^2$, $4^4$ in the denominator
\end{itemize}

\textbf{Required:} Simplified expression using laws of exponents.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
