\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Calculate the Slope of the Ramp}\\
Identify the coordinates of the two points: $(0, 2)$ and $(6, 5)$. Use the slope formula $m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$.
\begin{align*}
m &= \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1} \\
m &= \frac{5 - 2}{6 - 0} \\
m &= \frac{3}{6} \\
m &= 0.5
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 2: Determine the Y-Intercept}\\
Use the point-slope form equation with point $(0, 2)$. Since the $x$-coordinate is 0, the y-intercept $b$ is directly 2.
\begin{align*}
2 &= 0.5(0) + b \\
b &= 2
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Formulate the Equation of the Line}\\
Combine the slope and y-intercept into the line equation. Verify by checking both given points satisfy the equation.
\begin{align*}
y &= 0.5x + 2
\end{align*}

\textit{Verification:} At $x = 0$: $y = 0.5(0) + 2 = 2$ \checkmark\\
At $x = 6$: $y = 0.5(6) + 2 = 3 + 2 = 5$ \checkmark

\[\boxed{y = 0.5x + 2}\]
\end{solutionbox}
\begin{notebox}
\begin{itemize}
\item The slope of a line is determined by the vertical change divided by the horizontal change.
\item The y-intercept is where the line crosses the y-axis, valuable for forming the line equation.
\item Both slope and y-intercept are essential components in constructing the equation of a line.
\end{itemize}
\end{notebox}
