\section{Summary}\label{sec:summary}
\nopagebreak[4]

This chapter has presented the fundamental methods for determining the equation of a straight line. The slope-intercept form $y = mx + b$ provides immediate insight into a line's steepness and vertical position, making it ideal for graphing and interpretation. The point-slope form $y - y_1 = m(x - x_1)$ offers a practical approach when a point and slope are known. When two points are given, the slope formula $m = \frac{y_2 - y_1}{x_2 - x_1}$ combined with the point-slope form yields the unique line through those points. Advanced applications involving geometric transformations, such as rotation about the origin, require applying transformation matrices to the coordinates and recalculating the line equation. These techniques form the foundation for linear modeling in engineering applications ranging from ramp design to robotic path planning.

