\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section*{Introduction}\label{sec:intro}
\nopagebreak[4]

The ability to represent numerical information visually is one of the most fundamental skills in mathematics and engineering. Graphical representations allow us to perceive patterns, relationships, and trends that might otherwise remain hidden within raw numerical data. At the heart of this visual language lies the coordinate system, a framework that enables us to specify the exact location of any point in a plane using just two numbers.

This chapter introduces the Cartesian coordinate system, named after the French mathematician and philosopher René Descartes, who revolutionized mathematics by bridging the gap between algebra and geometry. By establishing a systematic method for plotting points on a graph, Descartes provided the foundation for analytic geometry, calculus, and countless applications in modern engineering and science.

Understanding how to plot points accurately is essential for engineering students. Whether analyzing stress distributions in structural components, visualizing electrical signals, mapping terrain for civil engineering projects, or programming computer graphics, the skills developed in this chapter form the bedrock upon which more advanced techniques are built. We will explore the structure of the coordinate plane, learn to identify quadrants, master the technique of plotting points, and develop the ability to calculate distances between points using the distance formula.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{The Cartesian Coordinate System}\label{sec:cartesian}
\nopagebreak[4]

The \textbf{Cartesian coordinate system} provides a standardized framework for specifying the position of points in a two-dimensional plane. This system consists of two perpendicular number lines that intersect at a point called the \textbf{origin}. The horizontal number line is called the \textbf{$x$-axis}, while the vertical number line is called the \textbf{$y$-axis}. Together, these axes divide the plane into a grid where every point can be uniquely identified.

\begin{definitionbox}{Cartesian Coordinate System}
A \textbf{Cartesian coordinate system} is a two-dimensional coordinate system formed by two perpendicular axes: the horizontal $x$-axis and the vertical $y$-axis. The point where these axes intersect is called the \textbf{origin}, denoted as $(0, 0)$. Every point in the plane can be represented by an \textbf{ordered pair} $(x, y)$, where $x$ represents the horizontal displacement from the origin and $y$ represents the vertical displacement.
\end{definitionbox}

The ordered pair notation $(x, y)$ is fundamental to working with coordinate systems. The first number, $x$, is called the \textbf{$x$-coordinate} or \textbf{abscissa}, and it indicates how far the point lies to the right (positive) or left (negative) of the origin. The second number, $y$, is called the \textbf{$y$-coordinate} or \textbf{ordinate}, and it indicates how far the point lies above (positive) or below (negative) the origin.

The convention of listing the $x$-coordinate first and the $y$-coordinate second is universal in mathematics and engineering. This ordering is essential because the point $(3, 4)$ represents a completely different location than the point $(4, 3)$. The systematic nature of this notation allows for precise communication of spatial information across all technical disciplines.

In practical applications, the coordinate system may be scaled according to the problem at hand. For instance, when plotting temperature variations over time, the $x$-axis might represent hours while the $y$-axis represents degrees Celsius. The flexibility of the Cartesian system makes it adaptable to virtually any situation requiring two-dimensional representation.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Quadrants and Sign Conventions}\label{sec:quadrants}
\nopagebreak[4]

The two axes of the Cartesian coordinate system divide the plane into four regions called \textbf{quadrants}. These quadrants are numbered using Roman numerals, proceeding counterclockwise from the upper right region. Understanding the quadrant system is essential for quickly determining the general location of a point based on the signs of its coordinates.

\begin{definitionbox}{Quadrants of the Coordinate Plane}
The four quadrants of the Cartesian coordinate plane are defined as follows:
\begin{itemize}[nosep]
\item \textbf{Quadrant I}: $x > 0$ and $y > 0$ (upper right)
\item \textbf{Quadrant II}: $x < 0$ and $y > 0$ (upper left)
\item \textbf{Quadrant III}: $x < 0$ and $y < 0$ (lower left)
\item \textbf{Quadrant IV}: $x > 0$ and $y < 0$ (lower right)
\end{itemize}
Points lying on the axes are not considered to be in any quadrant.
\end{definitionbox}

The sign conventions associated with each quadrant provide a powerful tool for rapid point classification. In Quadrant I, both coordinates are positive, representing points that are to the right of and above the origin. Quadrant II contains points with negative $x$-coordinates and positive $y$-coordinates, placing them to the left of and above the origin. Quadrant III houses points where both coordinates are negative, positioning them to the left of and below the origin. Finally, Quadrant IV contains points with positive $x$-coordinates and negative $y$-coordinates, locating them to the right of and below the origin.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.9]
\draw[thick,->] (-4.5,0) -- (4.5,0) node[right] {$x$};
\draw[thick,->] (0,-4.5) -- (0,4.5) node[above] {$y$};
\node[below left] at (0,0) {$O$};
\node at (2.2,2.2) {\large\textbf{I}};
\node at (2.2,1.5) {$(+,+)$};
\node at (-2.2,2.2) {\large\textbf{II}};
\node at (-2.2,1.5) {$(-,+)$};
\node at (-2.2,-2.2) {\large\textbf{III}};
\node at (-2.2,-1.5) {$(-,-)$};
\node at (2.2,-2.2) {\large\textbf{IV}};
\node at (2.2,-1.5) {$(+,-)$};
\foreach \x in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4}
    \draw (\x,0.1) -- (\x,-0.1) node[below,font=\small] {$\x$};
\foreach \y in {-4,-3,-2,-1,1,2,3,4}
    \draw (0.1,\y) -- (-0.1,\y) node[left,font=\small] {$\y$};
\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{The four quadrants of the Cartesian coordinate plane with their sign conventions.}
\end{figure}

Points that lie exactly on one of the axes have special properties. A point on the $x$-axis has a $y$-coordinate of zero, while a point on the $y$-axis has an $x$-coordinate of zero. The origin itself, $(0, 0)$, is the unique point that lies on both axes simultaneously. These axis points serve as boundaries between the quadrants and are not assigned to any particular quadrant.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{Plotting Points}\label{sec:plotting}
\nopagebreak[4]

The process of \textbf{plotting a point} involves locating and marking the position specified by an ordered pair on the coordinate plane. This fundamental skill requires careful attention to both the magnitude and sign of each coordinate. A systematic approach ensures accuracy and builds the foundation for more complex graphing tasks.

\begin{definitionbox}{Plotting a Point}
To \textbf{plot a point} $(x, y)$ on the Cartesian coordinate plane:
\begin{enumerate}[nosep]
\item Start at the origin $(0, 0)$
\item Move horizontally along the $x$-axis: right if $x > 0$, left if $x < 0$
\item From that position, move vertically: up if $y > 0$, down if $y < 0$
\item Mark the final position with a dot and label it with its coordinates
\end{enumerate}
\end{definitionbox}

The order of movements (horizontal first, then vertical) is a convention that helps maintain consistency. However, mathematically, the same point is reached regardless of whether one moves horizontally then vertically, or vertically then horizontally. The key is to ensure that the final position reflects both coordinate values accurately.

When plotting multiple points, it is helpful to use graph paper or a coordinate grid with clearly marked axes. Each small square on standard graph paper typically represents one unit, though this scale can be adjusted based on the range of values being plotted. For points with large coordinate values, a compressed scale may be necessary, while points requiring precision may benefit from an expanded scale.

Accuracy in plotting is crucial for engineering applications. A misplotted point can lead to incorrect interpretations of data, flawed designs, or erroneous calculations. Developing the habit of double-checking plotted points against their coordinate values is an essential practice that prevents costly errors in professional work.

\needspace{6\baselineskip}
\section{The Distance Formula}\label{sec:distance}
\nopagebreak[4]

Once points are plotted on a coordinate plane, it becomes possible to calculate the distance between them using algebraic methods. The \textbf{distance formula} is derived from the Pythagorean theorem and provides an exact method for computing the straight-line distance between any two points in the plane.

\begin{theorembox}{The Distance Formula}
The distance $d$ between two points $P_1(x_1, y_1)$ and $P_2(x_2, y_2)$ in the Cartesian plane is given by:
\[
d = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}
\]
\end{theorembox}

The derivation of this formula follows directly from the Pythagorean theorem. Consider two points $P_1(x_1, y_1)$ and $P_2(x_2, y_2)$. The horizontal distance between these points is $|x_2 - x_1|$, and the vertical distance is $|y_2 - y_1|$. These two distances form the legs of a right triangle, with the line segment connecting $P_1$ and $P_2$ serving as the hypotenuse.

\begin{figure}[H]
\centering
\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=0.8]
\draw[thick,->] (-1,0) -- (6,0) node[right] {$x$};
\draw[thick,->] (0,-1) -- (0,5) node[above] {$y$};
\coordinate (P1) at (1,1);
\coordinate (P2) at (5,4);
\fill[red] (P1) circle (3pt) node[below left] {$P_1(x_1, y_1)$};
\fill[red] (P2) circle (3pt) node[above right] {$P_2(x_2, y_2)$};
\draw[thick,blue] (P1) -- (P2) node[midway,above left] {$d$};
\draw[dashed,gray] (P1) -- (5,1) node[midway,below] {$x_2 - x_1$};
\draw[dashed,gray] (5,1) -- (P2) node[midway,right] {$y_2 - y_1$};
