\end{tikzpicture}
\caption{Geometric interpretation of the distance formula showing the right triangle formed by two points.}
\end{figure}

Applying the Pythagorean theorem:
\begin{align*}
d^2 &= (x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2 \\
d &= \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}
\end{align*}

Note that squaring the differences eliminates any concern about the order of subtraction or the signs of the coordinates. Whether we compute $(x_2 - x_1)^2$ or $(x_1 - x_2)^2$, the result is identical. This property makes the distance formula robust and easy to apply regardless of where the points are located in the plane.

The distance formula has numerous applications in engineering, including calculating the length of structural members, determining the spacing between components, computing travel distances in navigation systems, and measuring dimensions in computer-aided design software.

