\begin{solutionbox}
\textbf{Step 1: Plot the Points on the Cartesian Plane}

Identify the coordinates of each point: $A(-2, 3)$, $B(4, -1)$, $C(5, 6)$, $D(-3, -5)$. Use graph paper to accurately plot each point according to its coordinates. Ensure each point is labeled correctly on the graph.

\textbf{Step 2: Calculate Distance $AB$}

Apply the distance formula $d = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}$.

Substitute coordinates for $A$ and $B$: $x_1 = -2$, $y_1 = 3$, $x_2 = 4$, $y_2 = -1$.
\begin{align*}
d_{AB} &= \sqrt{(4 - (-2))^2 + (-1 - 3)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(6)^2 + (-4)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{36 + 16} \\
&= \sqrt{52} \\
&= 7.21 \text{ units}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 3: Calculate Distance $BC$}

Substitute coordinates for $B$ and $C$: $x_1 = 4$, $y_1 = -1$, $x_2 = 5$, $y_2 = 6$.
\begin{align*}
d_{BC} &= \sqrt{(5 - 4)^2 + (6 - (-1))^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(1)^2 + (7)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{1 + 49} \\
&= \sqrt{50} \\
&= 7.07 \text{ units}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 4: Calculate Distance $CD$}

Substitute coordinates for $C$ and $D$: $x_1 = 5$, $y_1 = 6$, $x_2 = -3$, $y_2 = -5$.
\begin{align*}
d_{CD} &= \sqrt{(-3 - 5)^2 + (-5 - 6)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(-8)^2 + (-11)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{64 + 121} \\
&= \sqrt{185} \\
&= 13.60 \text{ units}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 5: Calculate Distance $DA$}

Substitute coordinates for $D$ and $A$: $x_1 = -3$, $y_1 = -5$, $x_2 = -2$, $y_2 = 3$.
\begin{align*}
d_{DA} &= \sqrt{(-2 - (-3))^2 + (3 - (-5))^2} \\
&= \sqrt{(1)^2 + (8)^2} \\
&= \sqrt{1 + 64} \\
&= \sqrt{65} \\
&= 8.06 \text{ units}
\end{align*}

\textbf{Step 6: Sum All Distances to Find Perimeter}

Add all calculated distances:
\begin{align*}
\text{Perimeter} &= d_{AB} + d_{BC} + d_{CD} + d_{DA} \\
&= 7.21 + 7.07 + 13.60 + 8.06 \\
&= 35.94 \text{ units}
\end{align*}

\[\boxed{\text{The perimeter of quadrilateral }ABCD\text{ is }35.94\text{ units.}}\]

\textit{Verification:} Recalculate each distance separately and compare the sum to ensure accuracy; verify plotting on the Cartesian plane.
\end{solutionbox}

