\section{Summary}\label{sec:summary}
\nopagebreak[4]

This chapter introduced the fundamental concepts of plotting points on the Cartesian coordinate system. We established that the coordinate plane consists of two perpendicular axes—the horizontal $x$-axis and the vertical $y$-axis—intersecting at the origin $(0, 0)$. Every point in the plane can be uniquely identified by an ordered pair $(x, y)$, where the $x$-coordinate indicates horizontal displacement and the $y$-coordinate indicates vertical displacement from the origin. The plane is divided into four quadrants, each characterized by specific sign combinations: Quadrant I $(+, +)$, Quadrant II $(-, +)$, Quadrant III $(-, -)$, and Quadrant IV $(+, -)$. The process of plotting a point involves moving horizontally from the origin according to the $x$-coordinate, then vertically according to the $y$-coordinate. Finally, the distance formula $d = \sqrt{(x_2 - x_1)^2 + (y_2 - y_1)^2}$, derived from the Pythagorean theorem, enables precise calculation of distances between any two points, with applications ranging from perimeter calculations to engineering design specifications.

